Decoding Health with Data Science and Machine Learning

Date Mon 19 February 2018 By Brian Griner, Ph.D. Category posts. Tags Python Data Science Machine Learning Deep Learning Statistical Learning Biostatistics Diabetes Health Policy

Decoding Health with Data Science and Machine Learning¶

Examining Risk Factors Associated with Early Onset Type 2 Diabetes Among Pima Indian Women

by Brian Griner

Source: wikimedia

Motivation¶

The impact that diabetes has on patients is severe. The Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) cite diabetes as the leading cause of kidney failure, nontramatic limb amputation, and new cases of blindness in US adults. It is also a major cause of heart disease and stroke. and is also the 7th leading cause of death in the US (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. National diabetes fact sheet: national estimates and general information on diabetes and pre-diabetes in the United States, 2011. Atlanta, GA: U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 2011).

In addition to the impact on a patient's quality of life, diabetes also imposes a heavy financial burden on patients and our healthcare system. According to the American Diabetes Association, the total cost of this disease in 2012 was 245 billion dollars. 176 billion dollars went to direct medical costs and 69 billion dollars came from productivity losses (DIABETES CARE, VOLUME 36, APRIL 2013). A recent study published in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) ranked diabetes first overall in personal healthcare spending compared to other diseases and the costs continue to grow. The study also estimated the rate of spending by disease category between 1996 and 2013 and found diabetes spending growing at a rate of 6% annually (JAMA December 27, 2016 Volume 316, Number 24).

As demonstrated in these reports, diabetes is clearly a significant public health problem that warrants immediate attention from both the public and private sectors. While many medical studies on diabetes care and management exist, the prevalence of diabetes continues to increase as does the cost of diabetes care. Practical solutions are needed to control this disease in order to increase the quality of a patient's life while reducing the cost of care.

Questions raised in this post:

  1. What new insights can machine learning provide on how risks vary among different patient types, e.g. younger versus older patients, patients with and without a family history of diabetes?

  2. _Do diabetes risk factors have a casade effect that escalates the overall risk when several risk factors are present?

  3. What are the implications of varying and cascading risks on diabetes monitoring and management guidelines for patient types at risk?

The Pima Indians of Arizona have long been the subject of many medical studies over the years due to their high prevalence of diabetes. Since June 2006, the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases (NIDDKD) has sponsored an ongoing clinical trial to study pre-diabetes amongst this population. Cross-Sectional and Longitudinal Studies of "Pre-Diabetes" in the Pima Indians.

With such a high rate of diabetes amongst the Pima Indians, the obvious question is why? There is an ongoing debate among the scientific community of the role that "nature" plays versus "nuture" in determining the primary cause of diabetes. The answer to this question could have important implications for public health policy. Especially the extent to which diabetes can be prevented through behavioral changes such as diet and exercise (see links below for some examples).

Nature references

Nuture references

Commentary from the Indian Country Media Network on 'causal factors'

The role that risks associated with nature (e.g. family history of diabetes) and nuture (e.g. obesity, triceps skin fold thickness) are questions that will be considered in this research as will the interactions between nature and nuture risks to identify patient types with cascading risk profiles (i.e. biomarkers of high diabetes risk). To the extent that natural risks like family history can be mitigated by managing nuture risks such as obesity, the overall risk of diabetes can be decreased in all patients.

Pima Indians Diabetes Data¶

The Pima Indians Diabetes dataset used in this study was obtained from the UCI ML Repository, Lichman, M. (2013). UCI Machine Learning Repository [http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml]. Irvine, CA: University of California, School of Information and Computer Science.

Study Population: The population represented in this data is females, who are at least 21 years of age and are of Pima Indian heritage.

Attributes & Benchmarks*

  1. preg: Number of times pregnant
  2. gluc: Plasma glucose concentration a 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test - Pre-diabetes: 140-199ml/dl
  3. dbp: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg) - Metabolic Syndrome criteria > 85 mm Hg
  4. skin: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm) - female obese (21 years and older) >= 27 mm
  5. insul: 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml) - female norm: NA - overall 16-166 mIU/L
  6. bmi: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2) - overweight (25 to 29.9), obese (BMI >= 30)
  7. pedi: Diabetes pedigree function
  8. age: Age (years)
  9. class: Class variable (0 or 1) = False/True for onset of diabetes in 1-5 years

* Norms and diagnosis criteria for pre-diabetes and other related condigtions.**

UPDATE from UCI Repository: "Until 02/28/2011 this web page indicated that there were no missing values in the dataset. As pointed out by a repository user, this cannot be true: there are zeros in places where they are biologically impossible, such as the blood pressure attribute. It seems very likely that zero values encode missing data. However, since the dataset donors made no such statement we encourage you to use your best judgement and state your assumptions."

Methodology¶

Data Preperation and Preprocessing

In order to fully explore the underlying risk factors in pre-diabetes, and test for the existence of patient profiles with cascading risks, special care must be given to cleaning and transforming the input variables used for modeling as well as to the method used for imputation of missing values in the dataset. Thoughtful preprocessing of the data should enhance the ability to interpret the relative importance of individual risks and identify patient types with risk cascades that dramatically increase overall risk.

Algorithm Selection

The ADAP neural network was originally used with this data to predict pre-diabetes risk. This network is an adaptation of the perceptron discovered by McCullogh and Pitts in the 1940's (McCulloch, W.S. & Pitts, W. Bulletin of Mathematical Biophysics (1943) 5: 115). Much has been written about the limitations of using perceptrons for classification when the data is not linearly separable (Minsky M., Papert SA. Perceptrons: An Introduction to Computational Geometry. Cambridge(MA):M.I.T. Press;1969). While the ADAP network is a type of perceptron, it incorporates several excellent ideas to manage these limitations, such as sensors that categorize inputs into discrete ranges of nonoverlapping partitions and restrictions on connections between the input partitions and the output layer so that only one of the input partitions can be activated at a time during a training cycle. Moreover, the ADAP does a good job of predicting risk on the Pima Indians data (i.e. the crossover point for sensitivity and specificity is .76).

Given the many advances in machine learning that have taken place since the ADAP network was published, this study will test a broader set of machine learning algorithms to predict diabetes risk. Algorithm performance will be compared using 10 fold cross validation to determine accuracy and generalizability of individual model predictions.

For an example of how machine learning is used in biostatistics and observational research read Zagar AJ, Lipkovich I, Faries DE. Evaluating different strategies for estimating treatment effects in observational studies. Journal of Biopharmaceutical Statistics. 2017;27(3):535-553..

Interpretation of Risk Factors

Since the parameters of most machine learning algorithms don't lend themselves to direct interpretation like linear models, partial dependence plots will be used to graphically represent the relationship between the risk factors and the predicted likelihood of developing pre-diabetes.

For a detailed explanation of the use of partial dependence plots for interpretation read Hastie T, Tibshirani R, Friedman J. Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction. 2nd edition. New York (NY): Springer-Verlag; 2009. Chapter 10.13.2, Partial Dependence Plots; p. 369-384.

Descriptive and Summary Statistics¶

The first step in any ML analysis is to examine the data using summary statistics. These statistics address two important issues that can impact the quality of the analysis:

  1. Data quality issues: e.g., outliers and missing values can change the relationship between model outputs and inputs
  2. Distributions of inputs: ML algorithms are often more predictive when the inputs are standardized.

Insights¶

The percentage of prediabetes cases is 35% which should provide enough cases for a good classification model. Zero values in diastolic BP, triceps skin fold thickness, 2 hour serum insulin, and BMI are not biologically possible and represent missing values. Examining the 25% percentile of these attritubes reveal that triceps skin fold thickness and 2 hr serum insulin have at least 25% of the measurements missing, which can reduce the predictive power of the model and produce insights on risk factors that may be misleading. Given the importance of insulin levels and local obesity measures like triceps skin fold thickness in predicting diabetes, models for imputation to predict missing values for these measures will be explored below.

The skew statistics show negative skew for diastolic blood pressure and positive skew for serum insulin, pedigree, age, and the ratio of insulin to glucose. Large positive and negative skew statistics imply that standardization of these attributes should be performed to improve model accuracy.

Finally, a cross tabulation of the inputs against pre diabetes class show meaningful differences in the mean values and should be good predictors of pre diabetes; however, missing values coded as zero can artificially create these difference in the means, especially in triceps skin fold thickness and serum insulin levels where are a large proportion of missing values. This will be checked during the imputation modeling step.

Pre Diabetes At Risk Cases¶

In this analysis, we use the guidelines for diagnosing pre-diabetes to define the at risk population in the sample (i.e., those cases in the sample that meet the criteria for pre-diabetes or metabolic syndrome on a risk factor).

Similar to the ADAP network, we partition each input into discrete factors or sensors that determine if a case is at risk on a particular factor or not. Combinations of these discrete factors form a design matrix that is used to identify subpopulations within the sample with varying degrees of risk for pre-diabetes.

Insights¶

First we see that in general, pre-diabetes risk is two thirds higher for women 30 years old or older with no other risk factors. Of these women, pre-diabetes risk doubles if their glucose levels are elevated. The risk also doubles when elevated glucose levels are combined with high triceps skin fold thickness._

In women younger than 30 years old, baseline risk for pre-diabetes is half the baseline risk in older women. However, the risk in younger women increases by more than two thirds when glucose levels are elevated. This risk is even higher when combined with high triceps skin fold thickness.

Insight: In both age groups, women with elevated glucose levels are at high risk of developing pre-diabetes. Women under 30 years old with high triceps skin fold thickness or high bmi should have their glucoses levels checked to determine if they are at risk for developing pre-diabetes.

Next we examine genetic predisposition for diabetes, along with glucose and insulin level in both older and younger women.

Diastolic blood pressure has a complex relationship with other pre-diabetes risk factors, showing a cascade effect on risk when combined with high tricep skin fold thickness and elevated insulin levels. In older women, the combination of high diastolic blood pressure, high triceps skin fold thickness and elevated insulin levels more than doubles the risk of pre-diabetes.

In younger women, elevated diastolic blood pressure combined with high triceps skin fold thickness more than triples the risk of pre-diabetes.

Insight: In older women, the cascade of high blood pressure, high triceps skin fold thickness and elevated insulin levels doubles the risk of developing pre-diabetes. In younger women, high blood pressure combined high triceps skin fold thickness forms the risk cascade.

Imputation of Missing Values¶

Imputation of missing values is an accepted concept in healthcare research. It's use is particularly important when analyzing clinical trial data. See Ayele TA, Lipkovich I, Molenberghs G, Mallinckrodt CH. A Multiple-Imputation-Based Approach to Sensitivity Analyses and Effectiveness Assessments in Longitudinal Clinical Trials. Journal of Biopharmaceutical Statistics. 2014;24(2):211-228.

Machine Learning algorithms can be very useful for predicting missing values in the data. Given the importance of serum insulin levels and triceps skin fold thickness as risk factors for developing pre-diabetes and the large percentage of missing values, I will use a machine learning pipeline approach to test different algorithms and ensembles of algorithms. For other inputs with a very low percentage of missing values (i.e., plasma glucose, diastolic blood pressure and BMI), I will use a univariate strategy for imputation and replace missing values with the mean as it will have little impact on the analysis.

For a great introduction to this topic see Brownlee J. How to Handle Missing Data with Python. Machine Learning Mastery. March 20, 2017

For a detailed exposition on ensemble learning see Hastie T, Tibshirani R, Friedman J. Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction. 2nd edition. New York (NY): Springer-Verlag; 2009. Chapter 16, Ensemble Learning; p. 605-624.

In [8]:
# 1. BASELINE MODEL USING MEAN IMPUTATION

# MEAN IMPUTATION OF ALL ATTRITUBES USING SKLEARN IMPUTER
from pandas import read_csv, DataFrame
from sklearn.preprocessing import Imputer
import numpy as np

filename = 'pima-indians-diabetes.data.csv'
dataset = read_csv(filename, header=None)
# mark zero values as missing or NaN
dataset[[1,2,3,4,5]] = dataset[[1,2,3,4,5]].replace(0, np.NaN)

# fill missing values with mean column values
values = dataset.values
imputer = Imputer()
transformed_values = imputer.fit_transform(values)
dataset_imp = DataFrame(transformed_values)

from sklearn.discriminant_analysis import LinearDiscriminantAnalysis
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# split dataset into inputs and outputs
values = dataset_imp.values
X = values[:,0:8]
y = values[:,8]

# evaluate an LDA model on the mean imputation dataset using k-fold cross validation
model = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()
kfold = KFold(n_splits=5, random_state=7)
result = cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
accuracy = result.mean()
print("Accuracy of Linear Discriminant Analysis: %.2f%%" % (accuracy * 100.0))

# SAVE DATASET
np.savetxt("mean_imp_data.csv", dataset_imp, delimiter=",")

Accuracy of Linear Discriminant Analysis: 77.09%

Insights¶

Our mean imputation using Scikit-Learn's Imputer gives us a baseline validation accuracy of 77 percent using a simple Linear Discriminant Analysis to predict pre-diabetes. Using the XGBoost (eXtreme Gradient Boosting) model the validation sample accuracy jumps to 81 percent using the mean imputation dataset.

We will now investigate model-based imputation on the attributes with the largest number of missing values. Model-based imputation may or may not result in higher predictive accuracy but should provide more information about the underlying risk factors for pre-diabetes which is the goal of this analysis.

Machine Learning Imputation Models¶

To maximize information regarding the joint distribution of pre-diabetes risk factors, all cases with missing values are removed from the training and validation samples. The underlying assumption for removing cases with missing values is that these measurements are Missing At Random, i.e. the distributions in the new sample will be similar to the original sample. This will be checked.

For this analysis, the focus is on the two attributes that have the greatest number of missing values: triceps skin fold thickness and serum insulin levels. First, we model skin fold thickness and then model insulin levels. For this analysis, a machine learning pipeline approach is used to find the best algorithm for each input.

For more information on setting up ensembles in Python, read Brownlee J. Ensemble Machine Learning Algorithms in Python with scikit-learn. Machine Learning Mastery. June 3, 2016

Triceps skin fold thickness imputation model¶

We begin with the imputation model for triceps skin fold thickness. The approach taken for imputation is outlined below:

  1. TRAINING DATA: Remove missing values to maximize the quality of the data used to create the model.
  2. SCORING DATA: Impute missing values on the full dataset prior to deploying the imputation model.
  3. TRANSFORMATION OF INPUTS: Most ML algorithm perform better when the input data is standardized. If modeling counts, try taking the log(x+1) prior to standardization (to unlog - exp(ln(x+1))-1)
  4. MODEL TRAINING & TESTING: It is difficult to know which algorithm will perform best on any given dataset. Therefore, it is good practice to test several different ML algorithms on your data first.
  5. MODEL TESTING: ML algorithms should always be checked using a holdout or validation sample. It is even better to do so multiple times using Cross Validation (i.e. partition data into 5 folds. Use 1-4 to predict 5 then 1-3,5 to predict 4, etc.)
  6. MODEL TUNING: Once an algorithm is selected, the hyper parameters can be optimized using a grid search.
  7. SAVE FINAL MODEL: Once a final model has been selected, use Python's 'pickle' or sklearn's 'joblib' to save the model for imputation.
  8. IMPUTATION: a. Load saved model; b. Generate predicted values; c. Create new column with predicted values in dataset; and, d. Replace missing values with predicted values.

We start with the model of triceps skin fold thickness.

Insights¶

Of the individual models evaluated the Lasso Regression performed the best on both unstandardized and standardized data based on the Mean Squared Error (MSE) criteria. Of the ensemble algorithms, the AdaBoost model had the lowest MSE and prediction error; however, the Gradiant Boosting Machine (GBM) had the tightest range for the error distribution and was selected as the final model for imputation of skin fold thickness.

The distribution of tricep skin fold thickness is less skewed after imputation but can we do better by modeling the log of triceps skin fold thickness.

Insights¶

Of the individual models evaluated, the Linear Regression performed the best on the log transformed output on both unstandardized and standardized data according to the Mean Squared Error (MSE) criteria.

Of the ensemble algorithms, the AdaBoost model had the lowest MSE and prediction error; however, the Gradiant Boosting Machine (GBM) had the tightest error distribution and was selected as the final model for imputation of skin fold thickness.

The histogram of imputed triceps skin fold thickness using the log transform model shows a more normalized plot. This will help in the interpretation of risk factors later.

Serum Insulin Level Imputation Model¶

The serum insulin level imputation model is created using the triceps skin fold thickness after model imputation. Mean imputation is used on other inputs with fewer missing values.

Prediction accuracy of the Linear Discrimant Analysis remained the same at 77 percent and with XGBoost is 80 percent.

Key insight: Model imputation of missing values did not negatively impact the predictive accuracy of the pre-diabetes risk models.

Analysis of risk factors using model imputation data¶

Now that we have a complete dataset with no missing values and have checked it's predictive validity, we can proceed with the analysis of risk factors. With this newly imputed data, we can also examine a related condition, metabolic syndrome, in our analysis of cascading risk factors that multiply the overall risk of developing pre-diabetes.

Metabolic Syndrome¶

In this section we introduce a related condition, metabolic syndrome*. Metabolic syndrome is a cluster of symptoms involving abdominal obesity, hypertension, elevated glucose and cholesterol levels. Mexican ancentry is also a known risk factor given that the Pima Indians have settlements in Mexico as well as Arizona.

In an article studying the effects of insulin and glucose levels on blood pressure, C P Lucas, J A Estigarribia, L L Darga and G M Reaven Hypertension. Insulin and blood pressure in obesity. 1985;7:702-706, originally published September 1, 1985 showed a relationship between the ratio of insulin to glucose levels and diastolic blood pressure. This ratio may also interact with BMI or skin fold thickness and could imply the prescence of metabolic syndrome and increase the risk of pre-diabetes.

Insights¶

Using the imputation data, we see a clear picture of the risk factors for pre-diabetes and metabolic syndrome. For pre-diabetes, high triceps skin fold thickness when combined with elevated glucose levels is a risk cascade for pre-diabetes where risks double in women 30 years old and older and is greater than four times higher in women under 30 years old. For the metabolic syndrome risk cascade, the combination of family history of diabetes, high blood pressure and elevated insulin levels more than doubles pre-diabetes risk in older women and is five times higher risk in younger women.

Partial Dependence Plots for Identifying Pre-Diabetes Risk Factors¶

Gradient Boosting Machine¶

To examine the relative importance of different risk factors in pre-diabetes, I will use a Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM). GBM and ensemble version, eXtreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) have been referred to as one of the most power learning ideas in machine learning (Hastie T, Tibshirani R, Friedman J. Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction. 2nd edition. New York (NY): Springer-Verlag; 2009. Chapter 16, Ensemble Learning; p. 605-624).

The learning concept behind boosting and additive trees is that a set of weaker models can be combined into a committee of experts that greatly improves prediction accuracy. GBM is a sequence of simple models that are weighted and summed together to form the committee of experts used for prediction. Each model in the GBM sequence is tasked with predicting the error of the model that preceeds it.

Partial Dependence Plots¶

To identify the influence of individual risk factors in the GBM algorithm, the model prediction graphed over the input domain while averaging the other model predictors. This graph is called a partial dependence plot.

The python code used for the partial dependence plots was adapted from scikit-learn's example program using partial dependence plots.

In [18]:
from pandas import read_csv, DataFrame
import numpy as np
filename = "ln_skin_ln_insulin_imp_data.csv"
names = ['preg', 'gluc', 'dbp', 'skin', 'insul', 'bmi', 'pedi', 'age', 'class']
dataset = read_csv(filename, names=names)
# Compute ratio of insulin to glucose 
dataset['ratio'] = dataset['insul']/dataset['gluc']

from __future__ import print_function
print(__doc__)

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from time import time

from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble.partial_dependence import plot_partial_dependence
from sklearn.ensemble.partial_dependence import partial_dependence

# split dataset into inputs and outputs
values = dataset.values
X = values[:,0:8]
print(X.shape)
y = values[:,8]
#print(y.shape)

def main():

    # split 80/20 train-test
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,
                                                        y,
                                                        test_size=0.20,
                                                        random_state=1)
    names = ['preg', 'gluc', 'dbp', 'skin', 'insul', 'bmi', 'pedi', 'age']

    print("Training GBRT...")
    clf = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=4,
                                    learning_rate=0.1, loss='deviance',
                                     random_state=1)
    t0 = time()
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print(" done.")
    
    print("done in %0.3fs" % (time() - t0))
    importances = clf.feature_importances_
    
    print(importances)

    #print('Convenience plot with ``partial_dependence_plots``')

    features = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, (4,6)]
    fig, axs = plot_partial_dependence(clf, X_train, features,
                                       feature_names=names,
                                       n_jobs=3, grid_resolution=50)
    #fig.suptitle('Partial dependence plots of pre diabetes on risk factors')
            
    plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.1, right=1.1, top=1.4)  # tight_layout causes overlap with suptitle

    
    print('Custom 3d plot via ``partial_dependence``')
    fig = plt.figure()

    target_feature = (4, 6)
    pdp, axes = partial_dependence(clf, target_feature,
                                   X=X_train, grid_resolution=50)
    XX, YY = np.meshgrid(axes[0], axes[1])
    Z = pdp[0].reshape(list(map(np.size, axes))).T
    ax = Axes3D(fig)
    surf = ax.plot_surface(XX, YY, Z, rstride=1, cstride=1,
                           cmap=plt.cm.BuPu, edgecolor='k')
    ax.set_xlabel(names[target_feature[0]])
    ax.set_ylabel(names[target_feature[1]])
    ax.set_zlabel('Partial dependence')
    #  pretty init view
    ax.view_init(elev=22, azim=142)
    plt.colorbar(surf)
    plt.suptitle('Partial dependence of pre diabetes risk factors')
                 
    plt.subplots_adjust(right=1,top=.9)

    plt.show()
    
    # Needed on Windows because plot_partial_dependence uses multiprocessing
if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()

Discussion¶

The partial dependence plot of the pedigree function and insulin levels shows a cascading risks effect in the upper regions of the graph. When the pedigree function passes .6 (i.e. multiple direct family members are diagnosed with diabetes) and insulin levels climb towards 200 mu U/ml and higher, the risk of pre-diabetes increases dramatically.

If this finding can be replication in other studies, it points to an important public health insight: women who have parents or siblings that have been diagnosed with diabetes should have their insulin levels monitored periodically to provide an early warning of the cascading risk of developing pre-diabetes.

Knowler W., Barrett-Connor E., Fowler S., Hamman R., Lachin J., Walker E., Nathan D. Reduction in the Incidence of Type 2 Diabetes with Lifestyle Intervention or Metformin. N Engl J Med 2002; 346:393-403 DOI: 10.1056/NEJMoa012512
